## 6. Automated Decision-Making (POLA Act 2024)

{{ business_name }} uses AI tools for the following types of automated or semi-automated decisions that may substantially affect individuals:

{% for decision_type in automated_decision_types | default([]) %}
- {{ decision_type }}
{% endfor %}

### 6.1 Your Rights Regarding Automated Decisions

In accordance with the POLA Act 2024 (commencing 10 December 2026), you have the right to:

- **Know**: Be informed when an automated decision that substantially affects you has been made.
- **Understand**: Receive a meaningful explanation of the types of personal information used and the logic involved.
- **Contest**: Request a human review of any automated decision that significantly affects you.

### 6.2 Safeguards

We implement the following safeguards for automated decisions:

- Human oversight for all high-impact decisions (employment, credit, insurance)
- Regular testing for bias and fairness in AI decision-making systems
- Clear escalation procedures for contested decisions
- Documentation of decision logic and contributing factors

{% if pia_conducted %}
A Privacy Impact Assessment has been conducted for our AI-assisted decision-making systems.
{% else %}
**Action Required**: A Privacy Impact Assessment is being conducted for AI-assisted decision-making systems.
{% endif %}

{% else %}
## 6. Automated Decision-Making

{{ business_name }} does not currently use AI for automated decisions that substantially affect individuals. If this changes, this policy will be updated in accordance with the POLA Act 2024 requirements.

{% endif %}

{% if ai_tools_overseas and ai_tools_overseas | length > 0 and "None — all data stays in Australia" not in ai_tools_overseas %}
### 5.2 International Data Protection Obligations

Where {{ business_name }} processes personal data of individuals located in other jurisdictions through AI tools, the following obligations may also apply:

- **EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)**: If processing personal data of EU/EEA residents, {{ business_name }} must ensure lawful basis for processing (Art. 6), provide transparency about automated decision-making (Arts. 13-14, 22), and implement appropriate safeguards for cross-border transfers (Art. 46)
- **EU AI Act**: If deploying AI systems that affect EU residents, conformity assessments and risk management may be required for high-risk AI systems
- **UK Data Protection Act 2018**: Similar obligations to GDPR for individuals in the United Kingdom
- {{ business_name }} should seek legal advice on international data protection obligations specific to its operational footprint
{% endif %}

